In order to see the effect of the different condition to the binding of the TF, we performed a differential binding analysis. In order to determine the best mormalization method, we compared TMM normalization, normalization to 1, MAnorm normalization, and background normalization. Based on our plots, we chose the normalization to 1, but it is still not optimal. Indeed, with increasing number of proteins we would expect a larger number of binding.

Subsequently, we produced some heatmaps showing the top differentially-bound peaks. We can clearly see that in the FS30 condition and in the BLPM condition there is more signal, confirming again the previously explained findings (clustering). In addition, we can distinguish regions where there is more binding in specific conditions, e.g. BLPM, compared to the other ones.

Conclusion

Our analysis revealed clear differences between the stress condition and the baseline condition and also showed clear circadian effects by comparing the baseline condition measured early in the morning and the baseline condition measured late in the afternoon. Our results confirm previous findings explained in the literature, as explained previously in our analysis: Stress leads to a high glucocorticoid release, and this also happens late in the afternoon, just before the rat, being a nocturnal animal, starts its active phase.

By utilizing Upset Plots instead of Venn Diagrams, we revealed interindividual differences in stress response. The variability in response between animals is known and is thought to be partially explained by epigenetic mechanisms triggered by stressful early-life events ​(Ebner & Singewald, 2017).

When observing the upset Plots about half of the peaks result unique for the FS30 or BLPM condition, however when plotting these “unique” peaks on a heatmap, they are indeed not unique. This is a weakness of the original paper, where the initial part of the analysis relies heavily on overlap analysis. Caution is advised in making conclusions only based on overlapping, as there are two factors that can influence the number of overlaps that are found with the function. For one, depending on the order that the regions and tracks are fed into the function, different numbers of overlaps are found (Germain & Sonder, 2023). Additionally, the overlaps method is highly dependent on the thresholds that are set to determine whether an overlap is being counted as significant. Depending on where the thresholds are set, a different number of overlaps is the result (Brandes & Linial, 2016). Both aforementioned factors contribute to a variability in number of overlaps that can be observed.

The clustering approach helped emphasize similar signals and thus aided in depicting smaller differences between conditions, that would not be visible without clustering. This is especially helpful when comparing and distinguishing the MR and GR, as they have some overlapping functions.

The GO analysis did not yield any surprising results and, even with clustering, was very similar to the results of the paper. Still, the clustering results in more GO-plots, meaning more (cluster-specific) functions can be obtained.

The differential binding analysis did also not produce any unusual or unexpected results: Increased binding could be observed with a larger amount of proteins and increased receptor activity.

All in all, our recreation of the data was consistent with the analyses from the paper and did not yield any big surprises. Still, the clustering approach proved to be a better way of analyzing the data compared to simple overlapping, for the aforementioned reasons. The decision on what technique should be used is dependent on the individual goals and focus on detail.
